      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">In a previous special publication, NIST provided guidance for the
                compression of 1000 ppi fingerprint images using Part I of the JPEG 2000 standard.
                The present document extends the Guidance to the compression of 1000 ppi palm and
                whole-hand images. The NIST Spectral Image Validation Verification (SIVV) metric is
                used to determine JPEG 2000 compression ratios at which palm and hand images exhibit
                spectral fidelity to non-compressed source images comparable to that exhibited by
                fingerprint images compressed at 10:1. The investigators discuss the effect of
                untextured regions (i.e. large areas of low-texture or white space) in enabling
                compression ratios as high as 12:1 for palms and 22:1 for whole hand images as
                indicated by the spectral analysis. However, they note several factors that advise
                against deviating from the compression ratio recommended in the Guidance. Hence,
                NIST recommends that a single compression ratio, 10:1, be applied to all friction
                ridge impression types to ensure interoperability, in general, and support of latent
                matching, in particular.</abstract>
